1. What is VAT? Understanding the BasicsValue Added Tax, commonly known as VAT, is a consumption tax placed on a product whenever value is added at a stage of production and at the point of retail sale.
2. Unlike a traditional sales tax, which is typically only collected at the final point of sale to the consumer, VAT is collected by every business in the supply chain.
3. From the manufacturer of raw materials to the final retailer, each entity acts as a tax collector for the government.The VAT CycleThe Manufacturer buys raw materials and pays VAT.
4. The Wholesaler buys from the manufacturer and pays VAT on the "value added."The Retailer buys from the wholesaler and adds their margin.The Consumer pays the final price, which includes the total accumulated VAT.
5. The beauty (and complexity) of the VAT system is that registered businesses can often "reclaim" the VAT they pay on business-related purchases, ensuring that only the final consumer bears the full tax burden.62. 
